## @APGI-cmy

Please allow me to override this for now. This was actually authorised before ZWZDI, and its vital that all agents are trimmed and alligned before I start the cmpaign. One of the reasons for the critical failures recorded was .agnet file overloads. As we stand, I am unable to select some of the agnets. In the previous session we determined that I can only use caluse sonnet 3.5 as builders. We realsed taht some of the .agnet files were just too large to be cunsumed by teh actaul AI agents so it needed some serious re-allignment. If we do not implment this re-allignment we may face another failure like we just add. My request to you is t evaluate this: "Below is a structured way to streamline them so they:

Are short, directive, and ‚Äúloadable‚Äù by a Clause/Sonnet‚Äë3.5‚Äëclass model
Don‚Äôt duplicate governance canon
Still guarantee that no critical governance rule can be bypassed
I‚Äôll break this into:

What an .agent contract should (and should not) be
A concrete minimal schema structure for .agent files
How to avoid governance duplication but not lose coverage
How to help weaker models: ‚Äúpreload before work‚Äù + runtime prompts
Migration strategy for your current repo
Enhancement capture (per your own section 14)
1. What an .agent contract is vs governance canon
Governance canon
Purpose: Full doctrine: WHY, detailed rules, philosophy, edge cases, examples.
Audience: Humans + higher-capability agents.
Characteristics:
Long, narrative, justifications.
Cross-cutting, multi-agent, multi-repo.
May evolve and accumulate nuance.
.agent contract
Purpose: Per-agent behavioural operating system that:
Defines identity, scope, do/do-not, escalation rules.
Makes governance actionable in ~1‚Äì2 screens of text.
Audience: A specific model instance, often ~Sonnet‚Äëclass.
Characteristics:
Short. Think: 300‚Äì800 words, not 3,000.
Operational: ‚ÄúYou MAY / MUST / MUST NOT do X‚Äù, in the domains this agent actually touches.
Referential: ‚ÄúFor full doctrine, see governance/...‚Äù, not inline restatement.
Right now, CodexAdvisor-agent.md is doing both jobs. It‚Äôs mixing:

Canonical bindings (good)
Operational constraints (good)
Long-form governance education and philosophy (too heavy for the contract itself)
Your instinct is correct: those long sections belong in canon docs, not in the agent contract.

2. A minimal, high-impact .agent structure
You already have a good YAML core in CodexAdvisor-agent.md:

YAML
agent:
  id: CodexAdvisor
  class: reviewer
  profile: reviewer.v1.md

governance:
  canon:
    repository: MaturionISMS/maturion-foreman-governance
    path: /governance/canon
    reference: main

scope:
  repository: MaturionISMS/*
  allowed_paths:
    - "src/**"
    - "tests/**"
  restricted_paths:
    - ".github/**"
    - "governance/**"
    - "**/*.agent.md"
  escalation_required_paths:
    - ".github/**"
    - "governance/**"
    - "**/*.agent.md"

capabilities:
  execute_changes: false
  read_only: true
  advisory_only: true

constraints:
  governance_interpretation: forbidden
  scope_expansion: forbidden

enforcement:
  on_scope_violation: halt_and_escalate
  escalation_target: Foreman
Recommendation: treat that as the ‚Äúmachine layer‚Äù and keep it minimal and purely declarative.

Then, one short human-readable section beneath it, with:

Mission ‚Äì 3‚Äì7 bullet points.
Allowed actions ‚Äì 5‚Äì10 bullets, all verbs.
Forbidden actions ‚Äì 5‚Äì10 bullets, all verbs.
Escalate when‚Ä¶ ‚Äì 3‚Äì7 bullets.
Quick protocol ‚Äì 3‚Äì5 step checklist.
Example (condensed):

Markdown
## Operational Behaviour (CodexAdvisor)

**Mission (What you are for)**  
- Read code, tests, and docs.
- Provide architectural and quality advice.
- Flag potential governance or risk concerns.
- NEVER execute, modify, or approve anything.

**You MAY**  
- Summarize code and risks.  
- Suggest tests or improvements.  
- Point to relevant governance documents by path, not content.  
- Say ‚ÄúI am uncertain‚Äù and propose options.

**You MUST NOT**  
- Write or edit code, configs, or migrations.  
- Approve or merge PRs, or tell others to ‚ÄúLGTM, merge it.‚Äù  
- Interpret governance beyond explicit text in referenced docs.  
- Access secrets, `.env*`, or any sensitive data.

**Escalate to Foreman when**  
- Governance is ambiguous or conflicting.  
- A change touches `.github/**`, `governance/**`, or `**/*.agent.md`.  
- A decision affects security, compliance, or authority boundaries.  

**When answering**  
1. Restate scope: what you are and are not doing.  
2. Give advisory recommendations only (no imperative commands).  
3. If unsure, say so and explain why.  
4. If critical & unclear ‚Üí ESCALATE, do not decide.
That‚Äôs it. No philosophy sections, no authority pyramids, no full doctrine recap. Those stay in canon.

3. Avoiding governance duplication without losing coverage
Key design rule:

Canon owns the rules; contracts own the projection of those rules into one agent‚Äôs work.

So, instead of copying lists like ‚ÄúOPOJB/OPOJD, authority separation, no governance drift‚Äù directly into .agent files, do:

A short label + reference:
YAML
governance:
  canon:
    repository: MaturionISMS/maturion-foreman-governance
    path: /governance/canon
    reference: main
  bindings:
    - id: BUILDER_FIRST_PR_MERGE_MODEL
      path: governance/canon/BUILDER_FIRST_PR_MERGE_MODEL.md
      role: "builder-first-pr-merge-model"
    - id: GSR
      path: governance/philosophy/GOVERNANCE_SUPREMACY_RULE.md
      role: "governance-supremacy-rule"
And in the human section:

You operate under Builder‚ÄëFirst PR Merge Model and Governance Supremacy Rule (GSR).
Do not restate these; when needed, point humans to the canonical files above.
Your agent-governance-check.yml already bans certain patterns in .agent (e.g. BUILD_PHILOSOPHY, OPOJD, ONE_TIME_BUILD, doctrine:). That‚Äôs exactly the right direction: .agent should not carry doctrine text, just bindings.

4. Working with weaker models: preload + runtime scaffolding
You‚Äôre constrained to Clause/Sonnet‚Äë3.5‚Äëlevel builders; long nuanced governance will exceed their practical attention. You can compensate by splitting ‚Äúgovernance ingestion‚Äù into:

4.1. Preload phase (before work starts on any task)
For each agent-run, have a fixed bootstrap system prompt that loads:

The minimal .agent contract (YAML + short operational section).
A role-specific quickstart document, e.g. governance/templates/AGENT_QUICKSTART_CodexAdvisor.md, containing:
1‚Äì2 paragraphs of mission context.
5‚Äì10 ‚Äúgolden rules‚Äù (e.g., ‚ÄúNever change tests‚Äù, ‚ÄúAlways escalate governance ambiguity‚Äù).
Pointers (links/paths) to canonical docs if deeper reading is needed.
The quickstart is where you can be slightly more verbose, but still under maybe ~1,500 words.

Mechanically, that might mean:

In the Foreman / orchestration layer, every run for CodexAdvisor includes:
.agent ‚Üí as core config.
AGENT_QUICKSTART_CodexAdvisor.md ‚Üí as context, not as something the agent is allowed to edit.
4.2. Runtime micro-prompts
For each task, you can wrap the user prompt with a tiny agent-specific header:

‚ÄúYou are CodexAdvisor, an advisory-only reviewer. You MUST NOT modify or approve anything. You only provide recommendations and escalate on governance ambiguity. Refer only to the following files: ‚Ä¶‚Äù

Given that 3.5‚Äëclass models forget long doctrine, repeat key prohibitions every time:

‚ÄúDo not write code / do not modify files / no PR approval.‚Äù
‚ÄúIf unsure about governance, say you‚Äôre unsure and recommend escalation.‚Äù
This is cheap in tokens and extremely effective for behaviour.

5. Migration strategy for current repo
5.1. Refactor .agent contracts
For each existing .agent file:

Keep:

The YAML header, but:
Remove any doctrinal content, philosophy keywords, long text blocks.
Add governance.bindings for key canon docs instead of restatements.
A concise Operational Behaviour section as outlined above.
Move long prose into governance canon:

Authority models, pyramids, detailed escalation doctrine ‚Üí appropriate governance/canon/ or governance/philosophy/ files.
Cross-repo roles and responsibilities ‚Üí governance/specs/AGENT_ROLES_AND_BINDINGS.md or similar.
Enforce size / section limits:

You can extend agent-governance-check.yml to fail if:
.agent or *.agent.md > e.g. 200‚Äì300 lines.
Or if certain headings appear (e.g. ## Governance Philosophy, ## Canonical Principles) in contracts.
5.2. Create per-agent quickstart docs
Under governance/templates/agent-quickstarts/ (or a similar directory), create one file per important agent, e.g.:

CodexAdvisor.quickstart.md
governance-repo-administrator.quickstart.md
ForemanApp.quickstart.md
Each should contain:

‚ÄúWhat this agent does‚Äù (3‚Äì5 bullet points)
‚ÄúWhat this agent never does‚Äù (3‚Äì5 bullets)
‚ÄúTypical input / output examples‚Äù
Link list of must-know canon files.
These are human+agent docs, not contracts, and can be longer + more explanatory.

5.3. Ensure CI keeps contracts minimal and referential
You already have:

agent-governance-check.yml verifying:
presence of .agent
canonical binding key structure
no forbidden doctrine duplication patterns
mandatory restricted paths, escalation for .github/**
You could add:

A step to assert wc -l .agent < N (e.g. 250).
A grep to forbid certain heading patterns like ## Governance Philosophy, ## One-Time Build Law in .agent files.
Conversely, a check that governance.bindings refers to required core docs by ID or path.
6. Enhancement / improvement capture (per your own Section 14)
Your own CodexAdvisor contract requires end-of-review enhancement capture. Applying that here:

PARKED ‚Äî NOT AUTHORIZED FOR EXECUTION

Title: ‚ÄúAgent Contracts as Thin Behavioural Shells, with Canon-Bound Bindings‚Äù

Concept:
Refactor all .agent contracts to be:

Thin behavioural shells:
Small YAML with identity, scope, capabilities, bindings.
Short ‚ÄúOperational Behaviour‚Äù section (mission, allowed, forbidden, escalate, protocol).
Canon-bound rather than canon-carrying:
No doctrinal text in .agent.
Canonical governance lives exclusively under governance/**; agents only bind to it by ID/path.
Backed by quickstart templates:
Per-agent quickstart documents under governance/templates/agent-quickstarts/.
Loaded as part of the pre-run context by Foreman/runner.
Protected by CI:
agent-governance-check.yml extended to enforce:
No doctrinal duplication patterns.
Max line/size limit.
Required governance.bindings entries.
Routing:
This should likely be captured as a governance-improvement parking item under:

governance/parking-station/AGENT_CONTRACT_MINIMALISM_MODEL.md (or similar)"

